  "theory": "The Decimation-In-Frequency (DIF) FFT is an efficient algorithm for computing the Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT). While direct computation of an N-point DFT requires O(N²) complex multiplications, the FFT reduces this to O(N/2 × log₂N) through a divide-and-conquer approach.\n\nDFT Definition:\nX[k] = Σ_{n=0}^{N-1} x[n] · W_N^{nk}, where W_N = e^{-j2π/N} is the twiddle factor.\n\nDIF-FFT Algorithm (Cooley-Tukey DIF):\nThe DIF approach decimates (divides) the OUTPUT sequence X[k] into even-indexed and odd-indexed sub-sequences:\n1. The N-point DFT is split into two N/2-point DFTs using the periodicity and symmetry properties of W_N.\n2. For even k (k=0,2,4...): X[2r] = DFT{x[n] + x[n+N/2]}, n=0..N/2-1\n3. For odd k (k=1,3,5...): X[2r+1] = DFT{(x[n] - x[n+N/2])·W_N^n}, n=0..N/2-1\n4. This process is repeated recursively for log₂(N) stages.\n\nKey DIF Butterfly Operation:\nFor each butterfly, given two inputs A and B, and twiddle factor W:\n- Top output: A + B  (simple addition)\n- Bottom output: (A - B) × W_N^k  (subtraction THEN multiply by twiddle factor)\n\nDIF vs DIT Comparison:\n- Input Order: DIF has natural-order input; DIT has bit-reversed input.\n- Output Order: DIF has bit-reversed output; DIT has natural-order output.\n- Twiddle Factor Position: DIF applies W AFTER the butterfly; DIT applies W BEFORE.\n- Computational Complexity: Both require exactly (N/2)log₂(N) complex multiplications and N·log₂(N) complex additions.\n\nFor N=8 (3 stages):\n- Stage 1: 4 butterflies, twiddle factors W⁰, W¹, W², W³\n- Stage 2: 4 butterflies, twiddle factors W⁰, W²\n- Stage 3: 4 butterflies, twiddle factors W⁰ (=1, trivial)\n- Total: 12 complex multiplications vs 64 for direct DFT",
  "keyPoints": [
    "DIF-FFT input is in NATURAL order; output is in BIT-REVERSED order.",
    "Each butterfly: top = A+B, bottom = (A-B)×W_N^k — twiddle AFTER subtraction.",
    "For N-point DIF FFT: log₂(N) stages, N/2 butterflies per stage.",
    "Twiddle factors W_N^k = e^{-j2πk/N} represent phase rotation in the complex plane.",
    "DIF decomposes OUTPUT into even and odd sub-sequences (frequency decimation).",
    "DIT decomposes INPUT into even and odd sub-sequences (time decimation)."
  ],
  "useCases": [
    "Digital signal processing — spectrum analysis, filtering, and convolution.",
    "Audio and image compression (JPEG, MP3 use DCT/FFT variants).",
    "Wireless communications — OFDM modulation/demodulation in 4G/5G.",
